 It doesn't do anything in particular other than dump a bunch of data out.

00:06:29.000 --> 00:06:42.000
 If you're not authenticated, then I'm gonna construct a login URL by calling reverse, say lookup the URL for login, add a question mark, and then add the request path, which means wherever we're at, come back to it.

00:06:42.000 --> 00:06:58.000
 So that's the next, and that's gonna put next equals, blah blah blah, blah blah blah, and then instead of returning a render, we return a redirect and say okay, go to the login URL. So the way this is gonna work is it's gonna come in once, right?

00:06:58.000 --> 00:07:06.000
 You're not logged in, so it's redirecting, it's gonna go out, but then it's gonna come in back again, and this time the user's redirected in so it's gonna show you the page.

00:07:06.000 --> 00:07:18.000
 So you end up going through this twice. Now, that's the bad way to do it, or the wordy way to do it. I mean it's only five lines of code, but I don't like five lines of code.

00:07:18.000 --> 00:07:33.000
 So there's this thing called a mixin, and a mixin is a class. The idea of a mixin is that we have kind of an inherited class, we inherit things that are like just a feature almost, so what we're doing is we're gonna take our protect view.

00:07:33.000 --> 00:07:46.000
 It really extends a view, but it's gonna also add the capabilities of login required mixin. So login required mixin basically says to Django, if this is here, hey, I wanna do this.

00:07:46.000 --> 00:08:01.000
 Don't let the user into this particular view. You protect the view. So this is another protected view, but by simply including this little signal that says login required mixin, I've mixed this into my view, then it does all this work for us.

00:08:01.000 --> 00:08:14.000
 So what'll happen is, it won't even come in, right? It won't even come in if the user's not logged in. It will redirect, and then come back, and then let this code in the get run only when the user's logged in.

00:08:14.000 --> 00:08:23.000
 And so this is by far the most common way to do it, is just called login required mixin, saving you from writing all these lines of code, right? So all these extra things.

00:08:23.000 --> 00:08:33.000
 'Cause, do I remember how to do this? What if I write that 5,000 times in an application? It's really kind of silly when we've got login required mixin that takes care of all this stuff.

